/* ============================================================
   Reasoning GP — Audio library scripts (4 of 5)
   CKS-style clinician summaries. Dermatology · ENT & Eye · Paediatrics ·
   Palliative & General. ~5 min each: definition & lay explanation → risk
   factors → red flags → assessment → non-drug management → drug management →
   safety-netting → referral. Original summaries based on NICE CKS / NG.
   ============================================================ */
window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS = (window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS || []).concat([

  /* ---------------- DERMATOLOGY ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-acne', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🧴', dur:'5 min', title:'Acne vulgaris', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for acne vulgaris. Definition: a chronic inflammatory disease of the pilosebaceous units, producing comedones, papules, pustules, nodules, and potentially scarring. In lay terms, explain that acne happens when skin pores become blocked with oil and dead skin and then inflamed, that it is extremely common and not caused by poor hygiene or diet alone, and that effective treatments exist but take a couple of months to work, so persistence matters. Risk factors and aggravators include adolescence and hormonal changes, a family history, polycystic ovary syndrome, and some drugs. Assessment: ask about the duration, distribution over the face, chest, and back, previous treatments, and the impact on mood and self-esteem; in women, ask about features suggesting a hormonal cause such as irregular periods and hirsutism. Examine and grade the severity — mild, moderate, or severe — noting the lesion types and, importantly, any scarring or persistent pigmentation, which raises the urgency of effective treatment. Red flags: scarring or marked psychological distress should prompt more assertive treatment or referral, and acne fulminans, a rare severe systemic form, needs urgent referral. Non-drug management: give skin-care advice — gentle cleansing, avoiding picking and over-washing, non-comedogenic products — and set realistic expectations about the six-to-eight-week timescale and the need to continue treatment. Drug management matches severity: for mild-to-moderate acne, offer a 12-week course of a topical combination — a fixed combination of a topical retinoid with benzoyl peroxide, a topical antibiotic with benzoyl peroxide, or a topical retinoid with a topical antibiotic. For moderate-to-severe acne, add an oral antibiotic such as lymecycline or doxycycline for up to six months, always combined with a topical retinoid or benzoyl peroxide and never as antibiotic monotherapy, to limit resistance. In women, the combined oral contraceptive pill is an effective alternative or adjunct. Safety-netting and referral: refer to dermatology for severe nodulocystic acne or acne with scarring for consideration of oral isotretinoin, which is specialist-only and subject to strict pregnancy-prevention requirements and mood monitoring; refer urgently for acne fulminans; and refer for diagnostic uncertainty, treatment failure despite two completed courses, or significant psychological impact, supporting mental wellbeing throughout.' },

  { id:'cks-eczema', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🧴', dur:'5 min', title:'Atopic eczema', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for atopic eczema. Definition: a chronic, itchy, inflammatory skin condition that relapses and remits, often with a personal or family history of atopy such as asthma and hay fever. In lay terms, explain that eczema reflects a skin barrier that is dry and leaky and an immune system that over-reacts, that it is not contagious, and that the key to control is treating the dryness every day and damping down flares quickly. Risk factors include a family or personal history of atopy, and triggers such as soaps and detergents, heat, infections, stress, and certain allergens. Assessment: ask about itchy, dry, red skin in a typical distribution — flexural in older children and adults, and the face and extensors in infants — the relapsing course, triggers, and the impact on sleep and quality of life. Examine the distribution and morphology — dryness, redness, excoriation, and lichenification from chronic scratching — and assess severity. Red flags and complications: recognise bacterial infection with weeping and crusting, and eczema herpeticum — a herpes-simplex infection with painful, clustered, punched-out lesions and systemic upset — which is a dermatological emergency. Non-drug management is the cornerstone: generous and frequent emollients as leave-on moisturisers and soap substitutes, continued even when the skin is clear, plus identifying and avoiding irritants and triggers and good general skin care. Drug management: treat flares with topical corticosteroids matched to severity and site — mild potency on the face and flexures, moderate or potent on thicker skin and the body — in short courses, stepping up and down with severity; topical calcineurin inhibitors are an option for sensitive sites or where steroids are unsuitable. Use sedating antihistamines only short-term for sleep during severe itchy flares. Treat bacterial infection when clinically infected, and treat eczema herpeticum urgently with oral aciclovir, referring same-day if severe or near the eyes. Safety-netting and referral: educate on the treatment-ladder, review technique and adherence, and refer for severe or uncontrolled eczema, recurrent infection, diagnostic uncertainty, significant psychosocial impact, or suspected contact allergy needing patch testing.' },

  { id:'cks-psoriasis', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🧴', dur:'5 min', title:'Psoriasis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for psoriasis. Definition: a chronic immune-mediated inflammatory skin disease, most commonly chronic plaque psoriasis, associated with psoriatic arthritis and with cardiovascular and metabolic comorbidity. In lay terms, explain that psoriasis is where the skin cells multiply too fast, building up into scaly patches, that it is a long-term immune condition that is not contagious and tends to come and go, and that while there is no cure, treatments control it well. Risk factors and triggers include a family history, stress, infections such as streptococcal sore throat, skin trauma, smoking, alcohol, and certain drugs such as beta-blockers and lithium. Assessment: ask about well-demarcated, scaly plaques on the extensor surfaces and scalp, the course and triggers, and the impact on quality of life. Importantly, ask about joint pain and stiffness and screen for psoriatic arthritis, which affects a substantial minority, using a tool such as PEST, and ask about nail changes. Examine for the salmon-pink plaques with silvery scale, the scalp, the nails for pitting and onycholysis, and the joints, and assess severity and the body surface area affected; assess cardiovascular risk. Red flags: erythrodermic and generalised pustular psoriasis are rare emergencies needing urgent admission, and suspected psoriatic arthritis needs prompt rheumatology referral to prevent joint damage. Non-drug management: emollients reduce scale and itch, and support smoking cessation, reducing alcohol, weight management, and mental wellbeing, given the significant psychological burden. Drug management: for localised chronic plaque psoriasis, offer first-line a potent topical corticosteroid plus a vitamin D analogue, applied at different times of day or as a combined product, in a structured regimen with treatment breaks for the steroid; use tailored, milder preparations for the scalp and for flexural and facial sites. Safety-netting and referral: if topical treatment does not adequately control the psoriasis, or it is extensive or severe, refer to dermatology for phototherapy or systemic treatment including biologics; refer suspected psoriatic arthritis to rheumatology promptly; and review treatment response, technique, and adherence, addressing cardiovascular risk factors over time.' },

  { id:'cks-skin-cancer', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🔍', dur:'5 min', title:'Suspicious skin lesions', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for suspicious skin lesions and skin cancer under NICE NG12. In lay terms, explain that you are checking a mole or skin spot for any features that suggest it needs a specialist look, that most such lesions are harmless, and that catching any skin cancer early gives an excellent outcome. Risk factors include fair skin that burns easily, high or intermittent intense sun exposure and sunburns especially in childhood, sunbed use, many or atypical moles, increasing age, immunosuppression, and a personal or family history of skin cancer. Assessment: for a pigmented lesion, ask about a new or changing mole — change in size, shape, or colour, itching, bleeding, or oozing. Examine the lesion using the ABCDE rule — Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation, Diameter over 6 millimetres, and Evolution — and apply the weighted seven-point checklist, where change in size, shape, or colour each score two points as major features, and inflammation, crusting or bleeding, sensory change, and diameter of 7 millimetres or more score one point each as minor features. Use dermoscopy if trained. Recognise non-melanoma types: basal cell carcinoma as a slow-growing, pearly, telangiectatic nodule that may ulcerate, and squamous cell carcinoma as a faster-growing, scaly, indurated, or ulcerated lesion. Red flags and referral thresholds: refer suspected melanoma — a weighted seven-point score of 3 or more, any major feature, or dermoscopy suspicion — on a suspected cancer pathway for an appointment within two weeks; refer suspected squamous cell carcinoma on a suspected cancer pathway; and refer basal cell carcinomas routinely, unless there is particular concern such as a high-risk site. Management: consider photographing and reviewing equivocal pigmented lesions over a short interval rather than dismissing them, and importantly avoid excising a suspected melanoma in primary care, which can compromise staging. Non-drug management — prevention — applies to all: give sun-protection advice, including avoiding sunburn and sunbeds and using high-factor sunscreen. Safety-netting: advise the person to return promptly if a lesion changes, and ensure clear follow-up of histology and referral outcomes.' },

  { id:'cks-cellulitis', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Cellulitis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for cellulitis. Definition: an acute bacterial infection of the dermis and subcutaneous tissue, usually of a lower limb, commonly caused by streptococci or staphylococci. In lay terms, explain that bacteria have entered through a break in the skin and caused a spreading skin infection, that it is treated with antibiotics and elevation, and that you will mark the edge so any spread can be seen. Risk factors include a break in the skin such as a wound, ulcer, or athlete\u2019s foot, chronic oedema or lymphoedema, venous insufficiency, obesity, diabetes, and previous cellulitis. Assessment: ask about a spreading area of red, hot, swollen, tender skin, often with a portal of entry, and systemic features such as fever and malaise. A crucial pitfall: bilateral lower-limb redness is rarely cellulitis and is usually venous eczema, lipodermatosclerosis, or chronic oedema, so be cautious about diagnosing bilateral cellulitis. Examine the affected area, mark the border to monitor progression, check observations for systemic involvement, and look for the source of entry; use the Eron classification to grade severity. Red flags: consider deep vein thrombosis, and the surgical emergency of necrotising fasciitis — suggested by pain out of proportion to the appearance, rapid spread, skin discolouration or crepitus, and systemic toxicity. Investigate with inflammatory markers if systemically unwell, and swab only broken skin or discharge. Non-drug management: elevate the affected limb, give analgesia, mark and document the extent, and treat the underlying cause such as tinea pedis or a leg ulcer, managing oedema. Drug management: treat with oral antibiotics according to local guidance — flucloxacillin first-line, with a macrolide such as clarithromycin or doxycycline if penicillin-allergic. Safety-netting and referral: safety-net to return for spread beyond the marked border, systemic deterioration, or failure to improve; admit for severe or rapidly spreading infection, sepsis, Eron class 3 or 4, facial or periorbital cellulitis, or failure of oral treatment; treat suspected necrotising fasciitis as a surgical emergency; and consider antibiotic prophylaxis for recurrent cellulitis.' },

  { id:'cks-leg-ulcer', cat:'Dermatology', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Leg ulcers', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for leg ulcers, most commonly venous leg ulcers. Definition: a break in the skin below the knee that has not healed within about two weeks, with venous disease the usual cause, though arterial disease, diabetes, and other causes occur. In lay terms, explain that the ulcer is usually due to poor vein drainage causing pressure and skin breakdown, and that the key treatment — firm compression bandaging once we have checked the arteries are healthy — helps it heal and prevents recurrence. Risk factors include previous deep vein thrombosis, varicose veins, obesity, immobility, increasing age, and, for arterial ulcers, smoking, diabetes, and peripheral arterial disease. Assessment: ask about the duration, pain, and a history of venous or arterial disease. Examine the ulcer — a venous ulcer is typically shallow, in the gaiter area above the ankle, with venous skin changes such as haemosiderin staining, varicose eczema, and oedema — and assess the surrounding skin and signs of infection. A crucial safety step: assess the arterial supply before applying compression by measuring the ankle-brachial pressure index, where a value of around 0.8 or above generally supports safe compression, while a low index indicates arterial disease and the need for vascular referral. Red flags: an atypical, non-healing, or rolled-edge ulcer should be biopsied or referred to exclude malignancy, and signs of spreading infection or ischaemia need prompt action. Non-drug management is the mainstay for venous ulcers with adequate arterial supply: graduated compression therapy applied by a trained clinician, good wound care, emollients for the surrounding skin, elevation, mobility and calf-muscle exercise, and weight management. Drug management: treat clinical infection with antibiotics, but do not treat merely colonised ulcers, and manage pain and oedema. Safety-netting and referral: refer to vascular services for arterial or mixed ulcers, suspected arterial disease, an ankle-brachial index outside the safe range, and for assessment of superficial venous reflux, which may benefit from intervention; refer non-healing or atypical ulcers; and after healing, continue compression hosiery to prevent recurrence and review.' },

  /* ---------------- ENT & EYE ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-sore-throat', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'👄', dur:'5 min', title:'Sore throat & tonsillitis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for acute sore throat. Definition: an acute upper respiratory infection causing pharyngitis or tonsillitis, most often viral and self-limiting. In lay terms, reassure the patient that most sore throats are caused by viruses, settle by themselves within about a week, and do not need antibiotics, which make little difference and carry side effects, while explaining the self-care that genuinely helps. Risk factors and context include winter viral circulation and close contacts; glandular fever should be considered in adolescents and young adults. Assessment: ask about throat pain, pain on swallowing, fever, cough, and duration, and use a clinical scoring tool — FeverPAIN or Centor — to estimate the likelihood of streptococcal infection and guide antibiotic use. Examine the throat and tonsils for swelling and exudate, feel for tender cervical nodes, look for unilateral swelling displacing the uvula, and check observations; a throat swab is not routinely needed. Red flags: identify difficulty breathing or swallowing saliva, drooling, a muffled "hot-potato" voice, and trismus, which suggest a peritonsillar abscess or, rarely, epiglottitis — emergencies; and recognise that persistent unilateral sore throat, an unexplained neck lump, or persistent symptoms with risk factors raise head and neck cancer concern under NG12. Non-drug management: offer self-care advice — adequate fluids, rest, and simple measures such as medicated lozenges or salt-water gargles — and reassurance about the self-limiting course. Drug management: offer analgesia such as paracetamol or ibuprofen, and use the FeverPAIN or Centor score to target antibiotics — higher scores increase the likelihood of benefit, when phenoxymethylpenicillin is first-line, with a macrolide if penicillin-allergic; a back-up prescription is a useful strategy for intermediate scores. Avoid amoxicillin if glandular fever is possible because of the rash. Safety-netting and referral: admit for airway concern, suspected peritonsillar abscess or epiglottitis, or inability to swallow fluids; refer persistent unilateral symptoms or an unexplained neck lump on a suspected cancer pathway; and safety-net to return for worsening swallowing, breathing, or systemic illness.' },

  { id:'cks-otitis-media', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'👂', dur:'5 min', title:'Acute otitis media', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for acute otitis media, mainly in children. Definition: acute inflammation of the middle ear with an effusion and signs of infection. In lay terms, reassure parents that ear infections are very common in young children, are usually caused by viruses following a cold, and most settle within a few days with pain relief alone, so antibiotics are often not needed. Risk factors include young age, attending nursery, bottle-feeding, parental smoking, and a cleft palate or Down syndrome. Assessment: ask about ear pain, or ear-tugging and irritability in young children, fever, reduced hearing, and ear discharge, which often relieves the pain if the eardrum perforates, and assess how systemically unwell the child is. Examine with otoscopy, looking for a red, yellow, or cloudy bulging tympanic membrane, loss of the normal landmarks and light reflex, or discharge if perforated, and check temperature and general condition. Red flags: look for the rare complication of mastoiditis — postauricular swelling, redness, and tenderness with a protruding pinna — and for signs of intracranial complications or serious illness. Non-drug management: prioritise adequate analgesia with paracetamol or ibuprofen, which is the mainstay, with reassurance and clear safety-netting. Drug management: most cases are self-limiting, so offer a no-antibiotic or back-up antibiotic strategy for most children; consider an immediate antibiotic — amoxicillin first-line, a macrolide if penicillin-allergic — for children who are systemically very unwell, at high risk of complications, under two years with bilateral infection, or with a discharging perforation. Advise that recovery and any effusion may take time. Safety-netting and referral: refer urgently for suspected mastoiditis, intracranial complications, or other serious illness; arrange follow-up for persistent effusion affecting hearing or speech, which may indicate glue ear needing audiology and ENT assessment; reassure parents that recurrence is common; and review children with frequent infections.' },

  { id:'cks-hearing-loss', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'👂', dur:'5 min', title:'Hearing loss & tinnitus', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hearing loss and tinnitus. In lay terms, explain that hearing loss can come from a blockage such as wax or fluid (conductive) or from the inner ear or nerve (sensorineural), that hearing aids genuinely help and may protect against isolation and memory decline, and that tinnitus — noise heard without an external source — is common and usually manageable. Risk factors include increasing age, noise exposure, ototoxic drugs, family history, and ear disease. Assessment: ask about the onset and speed — distinguishing the emergency of sudden sensorineural hearing loss — whether one or both ears are affected, and associated tinnitus, vertigo, ear discharge, or pain, plus noise exposure and drugs. Examine with otoscopy for wax, effusion, or perforation, and perform Rinne and Weber tuning-fork tests to distinguish conductive from sensorineural loss. Red flags: a crucial one is unilateral or asymmetrical sensorineural hearing loss or tinnitus, which can indicate a vestibular schwannoma, and any associated neurological signs; and pulsatile tinnitus needs further assessment. Investigate with pure-tone audiometry, and arrange MRI for asymmetrical sensorineural loss. Non-drug management: treat reversible conductive causes — remove ear wax and treat middle-ear effusion or otitis externa — give noise-protection advice, and for tinnitus offer reassurance and support such as sound therapy and psychological approaches for distress. Drug and specialist management: a vital safety point is that sudden sensorineural hearing loss, developing over up to three days, needs urgent same-day or immediate ENT referral, as prompt high-dose corticosteroid treatment can recover hearing. Safety-netting and referral: refer asymmetrical or unexplained sensorineural hearing loss for imaging to exclude a schwannoma; refer adults with persistent hearing loss to audiology for assessment and hearing aids; and refer tinnitus that is unilateral, pulsatile, associated with neurological signs, or causing significant distress, reviewing and supporting the person throughout.' },

  { id:'cks-red-eye', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'👁️', dur:'5 min', title:'The acute red eye', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for the acute red eye. The priority is to distinguish benign surface causes from sight-threatening intraocular disease. In lay terms, explain that most red eyes are due to minor surface problems that settle, but that certain warning signs — loss of vision, severe pain, or marked light sensitivity — mean the eye needs to be seen urgently to protect sight. Risk factors for serious causes include contact-lens wear, trauma, and chemical exposure. Assessment: ask about pain — a gritty or burning discomfort suggests a surface cause such as conjunctivitis, while deep aching pain, photophobia, and reduced vision are red flags for serious intraocular disease — and about discharge, contact-lens wear, trauma, and whether one or both eyes are affected. Crucially, assess and record visual acuity in every red eye. Examine the pattern of redness, the pupil size and reactions, and the cornea, and stain with fluorescein to detect a corneal abrasion or the dendritic ulcer of herpes simplex keratitis. Red flags include reduced visual acuity, severe pain, marked photophobia, a fixed or irregular pupil, a hazy cornea, and contact-lens wear with a red painful eye. Non-drug management: for chemical injury, immediate and prolonged irrigation is the priority before anything else; advise hygiene measures for infective conjunctivitis, which is largely self-limiting. Drug management of benign causes: offer topical chloramphenicol for bacterial conjunctivitis if needed, and antihistamine or mast-cell-stabiliser drops for allergic conjunctivitis; manage a simple corneal abrasion and a subconjunctival haemorrhage conservatively. Safety-netting and referral: refer urgently or arrange same-day ophthalmology assessment for the sight-threatening causes — acute angle-closure glaucoma, with a painful red eye, headache, nausea, haloes, and a hazy cornea; anterior uveitis, with pain, photophobia, and a small or irregular pupil; scleritis; a corneal ulcer or keratitis, particularly in contact-lens wearers; and penetrating trauma or chemical injury. The key rule to convey: any red eye with reduced vision, significant pain, or photophobia warrants same-day specialist assessment.' },

  { id:'cks-rhinosinusitis', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'🤧', dur:'5 min', title:'Acute sinusitis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for acute sinusitis. Definition: inflammation of the paranasal sinuses, usually following a viral upper respiratory infection, with most cases self-limiting and only a minority bacterial. In lay terms, explain that sinusitis is usually the tail end of a cold causing blocked, painful sinuses, that it nearly always clears on its own over two to three weeks, and that antibiotics rarely help. Risk factors include a preceding viral cold, allergic rhinitis, smoking, and anatomical factors such as nasal polyps. Assessment: ask about nasal blockage, nasal discharge, facial pain or pressure, and reduced sense of smell, typically following a cold, and about the duration — symptoms beyond ten days without improvement, or worsening after an initial improvement, make a bacterial cause more likely. Examine for facial tenderness, the nasal mucosa, and exclude complications. Red flags: recognise the rare but serious complications — periorbital or orbital cellulitis with eyelid swelling, proptosis, or painful or restricted eye movements, and signs of intracranial spread such as severe headache, neurological signs, or meningism — which are emergencies. Non-drug management: most acute sinusitis is viral and resolves within two to three weeks, so advise self-care — analgesia, and consider nasal saline irrigation or short-term decongestants for symptom relief — and explain that antibiotics make little difference. Drug management: for symptoms present for around ten days or more without improvement, consider a high-dose intranasal corticosteroid, which may help; reserve antibiotics for people who are systemically very unwell, have signs of a serious complication, or are at high risk, when phenoxymethylpenicillin is first-line, or co-amoxiclav for severe cases, with a macrolide or doxycycline if penicillin-allergic. Safety-netting and referral: refer urgently or admit for suspected orbital or intracranial complications; refer to ENT for chronic sinusitis lasting over twelve weeks, recurrent acute sinusitis, unilateral symptoms, or suspected nasal polyps not responding to treatment; and safety-net for the warning features of complications.' },

  { id:'cks-hoarseness', cat:'ENT & Eye', ic:'🗣️', dur:'5 min', title:'Persistent hoarseness', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hoarseness, or dysphonia. In lay terms, explain that a hoarse voice is usually due to a viral infection or voice strain and settles, but that a hoarse voice lasting more than three weeks, especially in a smoker, needs a look at the voice box to rule out anything serious. Risk factors for laryngeal and head and neck cancer — the key concern — are smoking and alcohol. Assessment: ask about the duration — persistent hoarseness lasting more than three weeks is the central concern — and associated features such as sore throat, difficulty or pain on swallowing, a neck lump, weight loss, ear pain, and coughing up blood. Identify common benign causes — acute viral laryngitis, voice overuse, gastro-oesophageal reflux, smoking, hypothyroidism, and inhaled corticosteroid use. Examine the voice, the neck for lymphadenopathy and thyroid abnormality, and the mouth and oropharynx. Red flags and referral thresholds: under NG12, consider a suspected cancer pathway referral, for an appointment within two weeks, for people aged 45 and over with persistent unexplained hoarseness, or an unexplained persisting neck lump. Non-drug management: for hoarseness with an obvious benign cause and no red flags, treat the cause — voice rest and hydration for acute laryngitis, reflux measures, correcting hypothyroidism, and reviewing inhaler technique with a spacer and mouth-rinsing — support smoking cessation and reducing alcohol, and consider speech and language therapy for voice strain. Drug management is directed at the underlying cause, such as reflux treatment or thyroid replacement, rather than the symptom itself. Safety-netting and referral: the essential message is not to let persistent hoarseness over three weeks, particularly in a smoker over 45, go uninvestigated — refer for laryngoscopy via the suspected cancer pathway where the threshold is met, and to ENT for persistent hoarseness without a clear benign cause or not resolving despite treatment; safety-net to return if hoarseness persists or new features develop, and follow up to confirm resolution.' },

  /* ---------------- PAEDIATRICS ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-paeds-fever', cat:'Paediatrics', ic:'🌡️', dur:'5 min', title:'Fever in under-5s', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for fever in children under five, following NICE guideline NG143. In lay terms, reassure parents that fever is usually a sign the body is fighting a common infection, that the height of the temperature matters less than how the child looks and behaves, and explain clearly the warning signs that mean they must seek help. Assessment: measure temperature appropriately for age, and assess the child using the NICE traffic-light system, which stratifies the risk of serious illness using colour, activity and responsiveness, respiratory signs, circulation and hydration, and other features. Record temperature, heart rate, respiratory rate, capillary refill, and oxygen saturation. Ask about the duration of fever, feeding and fluids, wet nappies, alertness, rash, and any focus of infection, and about immunisations and travel. Red flags: look for features of serious infection — a non-blanching petechial or purpuric rash suggesting meningococcal disease, neck stiffness, a bulging fontanelle, focal neurology, and signs of respiratory distress or dehydration — and identify any source; any red traffic-light feature signals high risk. Non-drug management: for children with only green features and no serious-illness signs, manage at home with clear safety-netting — advice on fluids, recognising dehydration and the non-blanching rash, how to access help, and that antipyretics are to relieve distress, not the fever itself, and should not be used routinely to try to prevent febrile convulsions. Drug management: use paracetamol or ibuprofen to relieve distress, not routinely together, and treat any identified bacterial source appropriately. Safety-netting and referral: children with amber features need a more careful assessment, a period of observation, or specialist paediatric advice, with safety-netting; children with any red feature — such as looking very unwell, a non-blanching rash, reduced consciousness, or severe respiratory distress — need urgent referral to paediatric services, usually by emergency ambulance. Never miss meningococcal disease or other serious sepsis, and always give parents clear written safety-net advice on what to watch for and how to get help.' },

  { id:'cks-paeds-wheeze', cat:'Paediatrics', ic:'🌬️', dur:'5 min', title:'Childhood wheeze & asthma', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for wheeze and asthma in children. In lay terms, explain to parents the difference between a child who only wheezes with colds and one whose pattern suggests asthma, reassure that both are common and manageable, and emphasise inhaler and spacer technique and a written action plan. Risk factors for asthma include a personal or family history of atopy — eczema, hay fever, and food allergy — and parental smoking. Assessment: distinguish episodic viral wheeze — wheeze only with viral colds in an otherwise well preschool child — from a pattern suggesting asthma, with symptoms between infections, triggers such as exercise, allergens, and cold air, nocturnal cough and wheeze, and a background of atopy. Ask about attack severity and frequency, feeding and breathing in young children, and family history. Red flags: in an acute attack, assess severity by the work of breathing — respiratory rate, recession, accessory muscle use — oxygen saturations, the ability to talk or feed, and air entry, recognising that a silent chest, exhaustion, agitation, and cyanosis indicate a life-threatening attack. Diagnosis of asthma in young children is largely clinical, as objective lung-function testing is difficult under five; in older children use spirometry and other tests per the current guideline. Drug management of an acute attack: give inhaled salbutamol via a spacer, stepped up by severity, with oral prednisolone for moderate-to-severe attacks; admit for severe or life-threatening features, poor response, or social concerns. For chronic asthma, follow the paediatric stepwise approach with an inhaled corticosteroid as the controller. Non-drug management: ensure correct inhaler and spacer technique at every opportunity, provide a written personalised asthma action plan, support trigger avoidance and smoke-free homes, and review regularly. Safety-netting and referral: refer for diagnostic uncertainty, poor control, frequent or severe attacks, or children under the relevant age threshold for specialist diagnosis; safety-net parents clearly about the features of a severe attack and when to seek emergency help; and review after any attack.' },

  { id:'cks-bronchiolitis', cat:'Paediatrics', ic:'👶', dur:'5 min', title:'Bronchiolitis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for bronchiolitis, following NICE guideline NG9. Definition: a common lower respiratory tract infection of infants under one year, usually caused by respiratory syncytial virus, peaking in winter. In lay terms, reassure parents that bronchiolitis is a common chest infection in babies that usually gets better on its own over a couple of weeks, that antibiotics and inhalers do not help, and that the main things to watch are feeding and breathing. Risk factors for severe disease include prematurity, age under three months, and chronic lung or heart disease or immunodeficiency. Assessment: ask about a coryzal prodrome for one to three days followed by a persistent cough, then increasing breathlessness and difficulty feeding, with symptoms typically peaking around days three to five; ask about feeding volumes, wet nappies, and any apnoea, and identify higher-risk infants. Examine for tachypnoea, subcostal and intercostal recession, nasal flaring, grunting, fine inspiratory crackles and high-pitched expiratory wheeze, and check oxygen saturations and hydration. Red flags: apnoea, low oxygen saturations, poor feeding, dehydration, and severe respiratory distress signal the need for admission. Investigations are not routinely needed; oxygen saturation guides severity. Non-drug management is supportive, as antibiotics, corticosteroids, and bronchodilators are not effective: advise parents on feeding little and often, recognising worsening, smoke-free environments, and clear safety-netting. Hospital management: admit, or refer for emergency assessment, infants with any of apnoea; persistent oxygen saturations below the guideline threshold; inadequate oral intake, around 50 to 75 percent of normal, or dehydration; or severe respiratory distress such as grunting, marked recession, or a respiratory rate over 70 — with a lower threshold in higher-risk infants and where there are social concerns or distance from help. Hospital care provides oxygen and feeding support by nasogastric tube or fluids as needed. Safety-netting and referral: reassure that most infants recover over two to three weeks with the cough sometimes lingering, advise the warning signs that need review, and consider palivizumab prophylaxis only for eligible high-risk infants under specialist criteria.' },

  { id:'cks-paeds-constipation', cat:'Paediatrics', ic:'🚽', dur:'5 min', title:'Constipation in children', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for idiopathic constipation in children, following NICE guideline CG99. In lay terms, explain to parents that childhood constipation is common and usually not due to any serious cause, that hard or painful stools set up a vicious cycle where the child holds on, and that treatment needs adequate laxatives for long enough alongside a calm, positive toileting routine — not blame. Risk factors and contributors include a low-fibre diet, inadequate fluids, painful or frightening past stools, toilet training, and intercurrent illness. Assessment: diagnose constipation from two or more features such as infrequent or hard, painful stools, large stools, withholding behaviour, and overflow soiling, which can be mistaken for diarrhoea; ask about abdominal pain, reduced appetite, onset, and toileting. Most childhood constipation is idiopathic. Red flags: screen for features suggesting an organic cause — failure to pass meconium within 48 hours of birth, faltering growth, gross abdominal distension, abnormal lower-limb neurology or spine, or onset from birth — which warrant referral rather than routine treatment. Examine growth, the abdomen for palpable stool, and inspect the perianal area; a routine digital rectal examination is not needed in primary care. Investigations are not usually required for typical idiopathic constipation. Drug management: if faecal impaction is present, suggested by overflow soiling or a palpable abdominal mass, start with disimpaction using an escalating dose of an oral macrogol such as a paediatric preparation, warning parents that soiling may temporarily worsen and it can take a week or two; follow with maintenance laxative treatment at an adjusted dose, continued for several weeks after a regular soft-stool pattern is established, and reduced gradually rather than stopped abruptly. Non-drug management: support with diet and fluids, a positive, non-punitive toileting routine with regular sits after meals, reward systems for trying, and clear explanation of the withholding cycle; do not use dietary measures alone as first-line. Safety-netting and referral: refer if treatment fails, if there are red flags or atypical features, or for ongoing difficulty, and review regularly to maintain progress and prevent relapse.' },

  { id:'cks-enuresis', cat:'Paediatrics', ic:'💧', dur:'5 min', title:'Nocturnal enuresis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for nocturnal enuresis, or bedwetting, in children, usually addressed from around five years of age. In lay terms, reassure the child and family that bedwetting is common, is not the child\u2019s fault, and that most children grow out of it, while explaining the practical steps and treatments that can speed things up. Risk factors include a family history, deep sleep, an overactive bladder, constipation, and emotional stressors for secondary enuresis. Assessment: establish whether the child has ever been reliably dry — primary enuresis if not, secondary if dry for at least six months previously — and ask about daytime urinary symptoms, fluid and caffeine intake, the pattern and frequency of wetting, constipation, snoring, and the impact on the child and family. For secondary enuresis, ask about possible triggers and screen for diabetes, urinary infection, and emotional stressors. Examine growth and the abdomen, and assess for constipation, which commonly coexists and should be treated. Red flags: daytime symptoms, recent-onset secondary enuresis, or features of diabetes or infection point to an underlying cause needing assessment. Investigate with a urine dipstick if there are daytime symptoms, recent onset, or features of infection or diabetes. Non-drug management comes first: reassure and explain, and advise adequate daytime fluids, reducing caffeine, regular toileting and voiding before bed, and treating any constipation; reward systems for agreed behaviours such as drinking well and using the toilet before bed — not for dry nights — can help, and avoid blame and punishment. Drug and device management: for children who need active treatment and are motivated, first-line is an enuresis alarm, which is effective with persistence and support; desmopressin is an alternative or for rapid short-term control, such as for sleepovers or where an alarm is unsuitable or has not worked, with advice to avoid excess fluid around dosing; combine treatments for resistant cases. Safety-netting and referral: refer to specialist or enuresis services for enuresis not responding to an alarm and desmopressin, daytime symptoms or suspected underlying pathology, or significant comorbidity, and review and support the child and family throughout.' },

  /* ---------------- PALLIATIVE & GENERAL ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-palliative', cat:'Palliative & General', ic:'🕊️', dur:'5 min', title:'Palliative & end-of-life care', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for palliative and end-of-life care. The aim is to improve quality of life through symptom control, holistic support, and anticipatory planning, alongside or instead of disease-directed treatment. In lay terms, frame palliative care to patients and families as care focused on comfort, dignity, and what matters most to the person, that can run alongside other treatment, and that planning ahead helps ensure their wishes are followed. Assessment: identify people who may be approaching the end of life, considering the surprise question — would you be surprised if this person died within the next year? Assess symptoms — pain, breathlessness, nausea, constipation, agitation, and fatigue — and equally the person\u2019s understanding, priorities, and preferences, including their preferred place of care and death, and assess the carer\u2019s needs and any spiritual concerns. Look for reversible contributors, keeping investigations minimal and comfort-focused. Drug management of symptoms: control pain using the analgesic ladder, titrating opioids such as morphine with regular and as-needed dosing, always co-prescribing a laxative and an antiemetic as needed; convert to a subcutaneous route, including a syringe driver, if swallowing fails, using correct opioid dose conversions. Treat breathlessness with positioning, a hand-held fan, and low-dose opioids, nausea with an antiemetic chosen for the likely cause, and agitation appropriately after excluding reversible causes such as urinary retention. Prescribe anticipatory, just-in-case medicines for the home — typically an opioid, an antiemetic, an anxiolytic sedative such as midazolam, and an antisecretory drug — for the last days of life. Non-drug management is central: positioning, mouth care, a calm environment, psychological and spiritual support, and carer support. Safety-netting and coordination: plan ahead with the person — complete a treatment-escalation or ReSPECT plan and a DNACPR discussion, consider an advance care plan and lasting power of attorney, and complete an SR1 to fast-track benefits; coordinate community nursing, the palliative care or hospice team, and out-of-hours handover so that crises are anticipated; and support the carer, including in bereavement.' },

  { id:'cks-tatt', cat:'Palliative & General', ic:'😴', dur:'5 min', title:'Tiredness / fatigue', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for the common presentation of tiredness or fatigue. In lay terms, take the symptom seriously and reassure the patient that, while a serious cause is uncommon, you will check sensibly for treatable causes and then focus on the lifestyle and mood factors that most often explain it. Risk factors and contributors include poor or insufficient sleep, stress, low mood, excess alcohol, sedentary lifestyle, and chronic illness or its medication. Assessment: explore the symptom systematically — the duration, pattern, sleep quality and quantity, mood, stress, diet, alcohol, and the impact on function. Ask about associated symptoms that point to a cause — weight change, thirst and polyuria, breathlessness, low mood and anhedonia, and joint or muscle symptoms — and review medications. Red flags: screen carefully for significant unintentional weight loss, fever or night sweats, and lymphadenopathy, which need investigation for serious disease. Examine for pallor, thyroid signs, lymphadenopathy, and signs of organ disease, and assess mental state. Investigate with a focused first-line panel where indicated — full blood count, ferritin, renal and liver function, glucose or HbA1c, thyroid function, calcium, and coeliac serology — adding tests guided by the history, and avoid over-investigation. Management: treat any identified cause, such as iron-deficiency anaemia, hypothyroidism, diabetes, or depression. Non-drug management is central where the history, examination, and tests are reassuring, which is common: explain this positively rather than dismissively, and address sleep, physical activity, mood, stress, and alcohol, considering depression and, where criteria are met, chronic fatigue syndrome. Safety-netting and follow-up: arrange structured follow-up rather than open-ended reassurance, as supportive review is itself helpful; safety-net clearly for red-flag features; and refer for unexplained fatigue with abnormal findings, suspected serious disease, or where specialist assessment is needed, managing chronic fatigue syndrome according to the relevant guidance.' },

  { id:'cks-weight-loss', cat:'Palliative & General', ic:'⚖️', dur:'5 min', title:'Unintentional weight loss', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for unintentional weight loss. In lay terms, explain that losing weight without trying is something worth investigating, that there are many possible causes — not only serious ones — and that some sensible tests now will help find or rule out a cause. Assessment: first confirm and quantify the loss, ideally with documented weights — clinically significant loss is often taken as more than 5 percent of body weight over six to twelve months — as it is a recognised red flag and a possible presentation of cancer and other serious disease. Take a systematic history across systems to find a cause: ask about appetite, gastrointestinal symptoms and dysphagia, cough and haemoptysis, fever and night sweats, mood and anxiety, thirst and polyuria, and review by cancer site; ask about diet, social circumstances, alcohol, drugs, and dentition. Examine thoroughly for masses, lymphadenopathy, organomegaly, and signs pointing to a system, and recheck the weight. Red flags: weight loss combined with other features — such as a change in bowel habit, dysphagia, haemoptysis, or a mass — points to specific suspected cancer pathways under NG12. Investigate broadly: full blood count, inflammatory markers, renal and liver function, calcium, glucose or HbA1c, thyroid function, and coeliac serology, plus urinalysis and a chest X-ray, with tests directed by the history, and FIT and CA-125 where relevant. Management: the priority is to identify and refer the cause, using the appropriate suspected cancer pathways where features point that way, and to address malnutrition with dietetic input and treatment of any underlying condition; address mental-health and social contributors, and support nutrition. Non-drug and safety-netting: where initial assessment finds no cause, which can happen, avoid simple reassurance — arrange a defined period of monitoring with repeat weighing and review, and keep a low threshold for further investigation, because serious disease can take time to declare itself. Referral: refer along the relevant pathways for any localising features or persistent unexplained loss.' },

  { id:'cks-falls', cat:'Palliative & General', ic:'🧓', dur:'5 min', title:'Falls in older people', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for falls in older people. In lay terms, explain that falls usually have several small contributing causes rather than one, that they are not an inevitable part of ageing, and that addressing those factors — especially through strength and balance exercise — genuinely reduces future falls and protects independence. Risk factors include previous falls, muscle weakness, balance and gait problems, poor vision, multiple medications and sedatives, postural hypotension, cognitive impairment, and home hazards. Assessment: ask all older people, at least annually, about falls. For someone who has fallen, take a history of the circumstances — what they were doing, any warning, dizziness, or blackout — and the frequency, distinguishing a syncopal cause, suggested by loss of consciousness, from a mechanical trip related to gait, balance, vision, or the environment. Review the medications carefully, particularly sedatives, antihypertensives, and drugs causing postural hypotension, and ask about fear of falling and the functional and social impact. Carry out a multifactorial assessment — lying and standing blood pressure, gait and balance such as the timed up-and-go and turn-180 tests, vision, feet and footwear, cognition, continence, and a cardiovascular and neurological examination. Red flags: a fall with loss of consciousness, an abnormal ECG, or a fall causing injury or with a serious underlying cause needs prompt assessment. Investigate with an ECG and bloods including full blood count, renal function, calcium, vitamin D, and glucose, and assess bone health and fracture risk. Non-drug management is the most effective: refer to a strength and balance exercise programme, which reduces falls; arrange a home-hazard assessment and modification through occupational therapy; and give footwear advice and walking aids as appropriate, addressing fear of falling. Drug and medical management: rationalise culprit medications, treat postural hypotension, optimise vision, manage continence, treat any cardiac or neurological cause, and assess and treat osteoporosis to prevent fractures. Safety-netting and referral: refer to a specialist falls service for recurrent falls, falls with injury, or a syncopal or complex cause, refer urgently for a serious underlying cause, and reassess periodically, coordinating multidisciplinary input.' },

  { id:'cks-thyroid-tests', cat:'Palliative & General', ic:'🧪', dur:'5 min', title:'Interpreting thyroid tests', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for interpreting thyroid function tests, a frequent task in primary care. In lay terms, when explaining results, describe the thyroid as the body\u2019s thermostat, with TSH being the brain\u2019s signal that goes up when the gland is underactive and down when it is overactive, and explain that borderline results often just need rechecking rather than immediate treatment. Assessment: thyroid symptoms are often non-specific — fatigue, weight or mood change, bowel changes, or palpitations — so tests are commonly checked to clarify a clinical picture. Ask about thyroid medication, recent illness, pregnancy, and drugs that affect the thyroid such as amiodarone and lithium, and examine for a goitre and for signs of under- or over-activity. Interpretation: assess the TSH first, as it is the most sensitive marker of thyroid status in primary hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. A raised TSH with a low free T4 indicates overt primary hypothyroidism; a raised TSH with a normal free T4 indicates subclinical hypothyroidism. A suppressed TSH with a raised free T4 or T3 indicates hyperthyroidism; a suppressed TSH with normal hormone levels indicates subclinical hyperthyroidism. Red flags and pitfalls: beware non-thyroidal illness, the sick-euthyroid pattern, during acute illness, when interpretation is unreliable and testing is best deferred and repeated on recovery; and consider central causes if the TSH and T4 move in unexpected directions. Consider thyroid antibodies where autoimmune disease is suspected. Management: treat overt disease on its own pathway. For subclinical hypothyroidism, consider a levothyroxine trial if the TSH is above 10, or if it is between the upper reference limit and 10 with symptoms or positive antibodies, particularly in younger people, and otherwise monitor. For subclinical hyperthyroidism, repeat testing and seek endocrine advice for a persistently suppressed TSH. Non-drug and safety-netting: repeat borderline or unexpected results in a few weeks to months rather than acting immediately, avoid testing during acute illness, interpret all results in the clinical context, and arrange appropriate monitoring intervals for those on treatment or being watched.' },

]);
